257
00:10:36.928 --> 00:10:38.179
materials.

258
00:10:38.388 --> 00:10:41.808
This is the first sample surface.

259
00:10:41.975 --> 00:10:44.394
Maybe they're from
two different buried objects.

260
00:10:44.561 --> 00:10:46.813
Yeah. the two look very distinct.

261
00:10:46.980 --> 00:10:48.898
Yeah. I agree.

262
00:10:49.941 --> 00:10:51.776
The behavior of this Type B ceramic

263
00:10:51.985 --> 00:10:53.486
under SEM analysis

264
00:10:53.653 --> 00:10:56.322
is quite different
than the Type A ceramic.

265
00:10:56.489 --> 00:10:58.241
We're not seeing any of the changes

266
00:10:58.366 --> 00:10:59.726
that we might have expected to see

267
00:10:59.868 --> 00:11:01.369
based on our previous results.

268
00:11:01.536 --> 00:11:03.246
I think it's pretty clear.

269
00:11:03.413 --> 00:11:05.182
we're dealing with materials
that are completely different.

270
00:11:05.206 --> 00:11:08.376
But what are they doing
inside of the mesa?

271
00:11:08.543 --> 00:11:10.962
So this is one we might look

272
00:11:11.087 --> 00:11:13.047
- at elemental analysis on?
- Yeah. we can do that

273
00:11:13.131 --> 00:11:14.465
- right now.
- Yep.

274
00:11:14.632 --> 00:11:16.217
Let's start with the Type B.

275
00:11:16.426 --> 00:11:18.011
Sure. We're going

276
00:11:18.178 --> 00:11:20.847
to take a spectrum of the elements

277
00:11:21.014 --> 00:11:24.309
- that are on the surface.
- Okay.

278
00:11:24.475 --> 00:11:26.245
It's one thing to see
the physical differences

279
00:11:26.269 --> 00:11:27.520
in these materials.

280
00:11:27.645 --> 00:11:29.522
But we need the elemental analysis

281
00:11:29.689 --> 00:11:31.691
of this stuff to make sure they truly are

282
00:11:31.858 --> 00:11:33.318
different from one another.

283
00:11:33.484 --> 00:11:36.905
Okay. So we're starting to see

284
00:11:37.071 --> 00:11:39.199
there is some oxygen.

285
00:11:39.324 --> 00:11:43.578
quite a bit of calcium. some phosphorus.

286
00:11:43.786 --> 00:11:45.705
and then trace amounts

287
00:11:45.872 --> 00:11:50.752
of silicon. aluminum.
iron. sulfur. potassium.

288
00:11:50.919 --> 00:11:53.630
and all these things are present
in the Earth's crust.

289
00:11:53.796 --> 00:11:55.798
Okay.

290
00:11:55.965 --> 00:11:58.593
Well. this isn't the answer we hoped for.

291
00:11:58.760 --> 00:12:01.554
but it might give us
the bottom line on Type B.

292
00:12:01.721 --> 00:12:05.058
These are the exact elements
that make up the Earth's crust.

293
00:12:05.266 --> 00:12:06.976
So Type B was likely made

294
00:12:07.143 --> 00:12:10.188
from materials that naturally
occur in the mesa.

295
00:12:10.355 --> 00:12:11.856
But what about Type A?

296
00:12:12.023 --> 00:12:14.901
We still don't know who made it
or how they made it.

297
00:12:15.109 --> 00:12:17.237
Can we compare that to the composition

298
00:12:17.403 --> 00:12:18.655
of the Type A sample?

299
00:12:18.821 --> 00:12:20.240
Yeah.

300
00:12:21.241 --> 00:12:24.285
Yeah. let me zoom in here.

301
00:12:26.746 --> 00:12:29.791
Okay. There is a stronger magnesium

302
00:12:29.958 --> 00:12:33.461
- that is multiple times higher.
- Okay.

303
00:12:33.670 --> 00:12:35.630
And a lot more aluminum than iron.

304
00:12:35.797 --> 00:12:37.298
Yeah.

305
00:12:37.507 --> 00:12:39.634
Far less calcium.

306
00:12:39.801 --> 00:12:41.970
They're significantly different
from each other.

307
00:12:42.136 --> 00:12:43.513
Okay.

308
00:12:43.680 --> 00:12:45.000
This just makes me more convinced

309
00:12:45.139 --> 00:12:46.533
that we're looking
at engineered materials

310
00:12:46.557 --> 00:12:48.434
- with Type A.
- Right.

311
00:12:48.601 --> 00:12:50.478
I think the most important takeaway

312
00:12:50.645 --> 00:12:52.605
from all the Type A materials
we found in the mesa

313
00:12:52.772 --> 00:12:55.733
is that they were likely
manufactured by someone.

314
00:12:55.900 --> 00:12:58.194
But who? And for what purpose?

315
00:12:58.361 --> 00:13:00.863
By continuing to study them. we might

316
00:13:01.030 --> 00:13:03.366
bring some kind of understanding

317
00:13:03.533 --> 00:13:06.828
if not closure to the mystery
of this anomaly in the mesa.

318
00:13:06.995 --> 00:13:08.371
I want to take a look

319
00:13:08.538 --> 00:13:11.124
at that layered metal piece that we found

320
00:13:11.291 --> 00:13:13.209
- in the mesa this year.
- Yeah.

321
00:13:13.376 --> 00:13:14.812
Yeah. it looks like
it was manufactured that way

322
00:13:14.836 --> 00:13:17.338
- intentionally.
- Okay.

323
00:13:17.505 --> 00:13:19.382
Ceramics in solid rock is just plain weird.

324
00:13:19.549 --> 00:13:22.969
And metal in solid rock
is even weirder. so.

325
00:13:23.136 --> 00:13:25.722
if the metal is another part
of the object or objects

326
00:13:25.847 --> 00:13:27.181
buried in the mesa.

327
00:13:27.390 --> 00:13:30.476
maybe figuring out
what it's composed of is the key

328
00:13:30.643 --> 00:13:32.228
to solving this whole mystery.

329
00:13:37.525 --> 00:13:39.610
- Wow.
- So there's a stronger...

330
00:13:39.777 --> 00:13:42.155
prevalence of iron in this sample?

331
00:13:42.321 --> 00:13:43.865
- Am I reading that right?
- Yeah.

332
00:13:44.032 --> 00:13:45.658
Can you zoom in
to get more precise data?

333
00:13:45.867 --> 00:13:47.201
Sure.

334
00:13:52.957 --> 00:13:55.460
Yeah. so what did
I just see happen here?

335
00:13:55.668 --> 00:13:57.045
- It just went dark.
- Lost...

336
00:13:57.211 --> 00:13:58.897
- We've lost the image.
- Yeah. it was on there.

337
00:13:58.921 --> 00:14:00.631
- and then it just went black.
- Yeah.

338
00:14:00.798 --> 00:14:03.593
I'm checking the filament integrity.

339
00:14:03.760 --> 00:14:06.637
Because in order
to produce an image. we need

340
00:14:06.804 --> 00:14:08.973
a source of electrons...

341
00:14:09.140 --> 00:14:10.933
Yeah.

342
00:14:11.100 --> 00:14:14.854
We have just blown our filament.

343
00:14:15.021 --> 00:14:17.231
This particular filament was actually only

344
00:14:17.398 --> 00:14:18.858
about halfway through its lifespan.

345
00:14:19.067 --> 00:14:20.568
according to the software.

346
00:14:20.735 --> 00:14:22.945
- Is that a big repair?
- Yes. it is.

347
00:14:23.112 --> 00:14:24.655
Which means

348
00:14:24.822 --> 00:14:28.785
we're dead in the water
until I can get that replaced.

349
00:14:28.951 --> 00:14:30.870
Interesting.

350
00:14:31.037 --> 00:14:35.374
The electron source. the
filament itself has burned out.

351
00:14:35.541 --> 00:14:37.168
I don't know why this has happened.

352
00:14:37.335 --> 00:14:38.669
The timing couldn't be worse.

353
00:14:38.836 --> 00:14:40.421
This is another one of those situations

354
00:14:40.630 --> 00:14:44.092
where things go exactly wrong
at exactly the wrong time.

355
00:14:44.258 --> 00:14:45.885
Is it just a coincidence?

356
00:14:46.052 --> 00:14:48.805
Do we assign special cause
to that? I don't know.

357
00:14:48.971 --> 00:14:52.016
The good news is.
we've only made our way

358
00:14:52.183 --> 00:14:54.393
through a small fraction of the spoils

359
00:14:54.560 --> 00:14:56.521
that have come out of our recent drilling.

360
00:14:56.646 --> 00:14:58.940
So by the time we come back.

361
00:14:59.148 --> 00:15:00.584
there could be a lot more
of this material up there

362
00:15:00.608 --> 00:15:03.194
to be collected and analyzed.

363
00:15:03.361 --> 00:15:05.988
Dr. Patchett.
thanks again for the analysis.

364
00:15:06.155 --> 00:15:08.008
It's always a pleasure
to have you guys on campus.

365
00:15:08.032 --> 00:15:10.535
All right. I think it's time to pack it up.

366
00:15:10.701 --> 00:15:12.870
All right.

367
00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:20.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

368
00:15:25.466 --> 00:15:27.093
All right.

369
00:15:27.260 --> 00:15:28.862
So. I think this is a pretty good spot. y'all.

370
00:15:28.886 --> 00:15:30.763
I mean. we've got a good view in here

371
00:15:30.930 --> 00:15:33.224
looking at Homestead Three.

372
00:15:33.391 --> 00:15:35.601
The following day.
we set up for a new experiment

373
00:15:35.726 --> 00:15:39.772
at Homestead Three. located
near the western property line

374
00:15:39.939 --> 00:15:41.566
of Skinwalker Ranch.

375
00:15:41.732 --> 00:15:45.194
I've not heard a lot
of history from this site.

376
00:15:45.361 --> 00:15:47.113
But we do have our own experience.

377
00:15:47.280 --> 00:15:50.992
And we've seen lights out here
when we were doing experiments.

378
00:15:53.202 --> 00:15:55.538
Homestead Three is one
of the abandoned

379
00:15:55.746 --> 00:15:58.666
early 20th-century dwellings
on the ranch.

380
00:15:58.833 --> 00:16:02.628
There's very little hard
documentation of the property.

381
00:16:02.795 --> 00:16:04.964
but its previous owners.
the Locke family.

382
00:16:05.131 --> 00:16:07.884
reported witnessing
all sorts of strange events

383
00:16:08.050 --> 00:16:09.468
while living here.

384
00:16:09.635 --> 00:16:11.846
from unexplained cattle mutilations

385
00:16:12.013 --> 00:16:13.848
to UAP sightings.

386
00:16:14.015 --> 00:16:17.768
In 2016. just after Brandon
Fugal purchased the property.

387
00:16:17.935 --> 00:16:20.563
he and Erik led a group
of scientific experts

388
00:16:20.730 --> 00:16:23.774
and private security
on a tour of Homestead Three.

389
00:16:23.941 --> 00:16:26.402
There. a security guard was overcome

390
00:16:26.527 --> 00:16:30.114
by something
that made him go catatonic.

391
00:16:30.281 --> 00:16:33.075
He ended up being okay.
but over the past six years.

392
00:16:33.242 --> 00:16:35.828
our team hasn't had
any other encounters there.

393
00:16:35.995 --> 00:16:37.496
That is. until last week.

394
00:16:37.663 --> 00:16:40.249
Thomas is starting to pump smoke now.

395
00:16:40.416 --> 00:16:43.711
We were several hundred yards
to the east at Homestead Two.

396
00:16:43.878 --> 00:16:46.464
investigating a recent UAP sighting

397
00:16:46.631 --> 00:16:48.174
and possible communication signals

398
00:16:48.341 --> 00:16:49.981
that we detected in one of the buildings.

399
00:16:50.051 --> 00:16:51.761
What is that all the way over there?

400
00:16:51.886 --> 00:16:54.055
Suddenly. Erik saw a strange light

401
00:16:54.222 --> 00:16:57.558
on a surveillance camera
appear over Homestead Three.

402
00:16:57.725 --> 00:16:59.285
When Jim Royston tried to track it down

403
00:16:59.435 --> 00:17:03.105
with his thermal drone.
the light disappeared.

404
00:17:03.272 --> 00:17:05.148
But then we were all shocked

405
00:17:05.316 --> 00:17:08.069
to see a massive heat anomaly
filling the main building.

406
00:17:08.236 --> 00:17:09.444
Look at the heat

407
00:17:09.612 --> 00:17:11.739
- coming out of the homestead.
- I know.

408
00:17:11.948 --> 00:17:14.532
It was like it was
on fire in the thermal camera.

409
00:17:14.700 --> 00:17:16.035
But with the naked eye.

410
00:17:16.202 --> 00:17:18.579
we couldn't see anything in there.

411
00:17:18.788 --> 00:17:22.208
So tonight we want to figure out
just what the heck that was.

412
00:17:22.375 --> 00:17:24.042
What I was thinking is. kind of

413
00:17:24.210 --> 00:17:26.410
repeat what we did at Homestead
Two with the laser grid.

414
00:17:26.587 --> 00:17:28.589
Maybe put it in this window
on the north side?

415
00:17:28.756 --> 00:17:30.424
And the smoke

416
00:17:30.591 --> 00:17:32.510
through the door?
Thomas. what do you think?

417
00:17:32.635 --> 00:17:34.053
Yep.

418
00:17:34.220 --> 00:17:35.888
Just like last week's experiment.

419
00:17:36.055 --> 00:17:38.641
we're going to use lasers
to project a grid of light

420
00:17:38.766 --> 00:17:40.434
inside of Homestead Three.

421
00:17:40.601 --> 00:17:42.812
Then we'll fill the building with smoke.

422
00:17:42.979 --> 00:17:44.897
The lasers and smoke combined
will allow us

423
00:17:45.106 --> 00:17:47.567
to look for anything
passing through the grid

424
00:17:47.733 --> 00:17:50.319
that might be invisible to the naked eye.

425
00:17:50.444 --> 00:17:51.988
Now. to add to that.

426
00:17:52.154 --> 00:17:53.757
I'd like us to try something
between Homestead Two

427
00:17:53.781 --> 00:17:55.658
and Homestead Three.
I'm convinced that there's

428
00:17:55.866 --> 00:17:57.493
some kind of connection between 'em.

429
00:17:57.660 --> 00:18:00.454
So I want to try transmitting
a 1.2-gigahertz signal here

430
00:18:00.621 --> 00:18:03.040
and see if it shows up
at Homestead Two.

431
00:18:03.165 --> 00:18:05.543
All right. I say we get to it.

432
00:18:07.003 --> 00:18:09.922
While the rest of the team
began setting up the laser grid.

433
00:18:10.089 --> 00:18:11.882
Erik and I wanted to run a little test

434
00:18:12.049 --> 00:18:13.593
to see if there's a connection

435
00:18:13.759 --> 00:18:16.137
between Homestead Three
and Homestead Two.

436
00:18:16.345 --> 00:18:18.347
During last week's experiment.

437
00:18:18.514 --> 00:18:20.808
after I broadcast a 1.6-gigahertz signal.

438
00:18:20.975 --> 00:18:23.769
something seemed to clone the signal

439
00:18:23.936 --> 00:18:26.647
and send it back to us
from inside Homestead Two.

440
00:18:26.814 --> 00:18:29.025
Where's that signal coming from?

441
00:18:29.191 --> 00:18:34.030
It was another case of something
unexplained cloning our signals.

442
00:18:34.196 --> 00:18:36.657
So Erik will broadcast a new test signal

443
00:18:36.866 --> 00:18:39.243
at 1.2 gigahertz from Homestead Three

444
00:18:39.368 --> 00:18:42.079
for a few minutes and then turn it off.

445
00:18:42.204 --> 00:18:44.123
At that point.
Kaleb and I will be monitoring

446
00:18:44.290 --> 00:18:46.876
our own spectrum analyzers
at Homestead Two

447
00:18:47.043 --> 00:18:49.086
to see if something clones that signal

448
00:18:49.253 --> 00:18:51.047
and starts broadcasting it again.

449
00:18:51.213 --> 00:18:52.632
All right. we're good to go.

450
00:18:58.554 --> 00:19:01.849
Hey. Erik. We're all set up here
at Homestead Two.

451
00:19:02.016 --> 00:19:03.434
Yeah. copy that.

452
00:19:03.601 --> 00:19:06.979
All right. let's see here.

453
00:19:07.188 --> 00:19:09.273
I don't know
what's happening right there.

454
00:19:11.484 --> 00:19:13.694
That's some kind of 1.2-gigahertz signal.

455
00:19:13.861 --> 00:19:16.322
See the peak right there.

456
00:19:16.447 --> 00:19:18.287
Erik. did you just
turn on the signal generator

457
00:19:18.366 --> 00:19:20.159
at 1.2 gigahertz?

458
00:19:20.284 --> 00:19:21.494
No. Travis.

459
00:19:21.661 --> 00:19:22.995
we haven't done that yet.

460
00:19:23.162 --> 00:19:24.664
What in the world?

461
00:19:26.207 --> 00:19:28.000
So where is this signal coming from?

462
00:19:31.003 --> 00:19:33.756
Man. that's just weird.

463
00:19:36.384 --> 00:19:38.094
What in the world?

464
00:19:38.260 --> 00:19:41.013
So where is this signal coming from?

465
00:19:41.180 --> 00:19:43.599
Look at it. It's just... I...

466
00:19:43.724 --> 00:19:45.309
I don't know what's going on.

467
00:19:45.476 --> 00:19:47.228
That's a pretty strong one.

468
00:19:47.395 --> 00:19:50.147
All right. man. That signal went away.

469
00:19:50.314 --> 00:19:53.192
It's not there anymore.

470
00:19:53.359 --> 00:19:55.736
That was the strangest thing.

471
00:19:55.903 --> 00:19:59.407
Before Erik even had the chance
to broadcast his test signal

472
00:19:59.573 --> 00:20:02.076
at 1.2 gigahertz from Homestead Three.

473
00:20:02.243 --> 00:20:04.745
I picked up that same frequency
for a few seconds

474
00:20:04.912 --> 00:20:06.831
over at Homestead Two.

475
00:20:06.997 --> 00:20:08.499
Before. we thought

476
00:20:08.708 --> 00:20:10.835
something was cloning
the signals that we broadcast.

477
00:20:11.001 --> 00:20:13.754
Now it's like it's reading our minds

478
00:20:13.921 --> 00:20:15.214
and beating us to the punch.

479
00:20:15.381 --> 00:20:18.134
What in the world could do that?

480
00:20:18.300 --> 00:20:19.844
That's really interesting.

481
00:20:20.010 --> 00:20:22.012
I wonder what that was.

482
00:20:24.056 --> 00:20:25.558
Ooh. Something weird has happened

483
00:20:25.725 --> 00:20:28.185
to this gamma ray detector.
Check this out.

484
00:20:28.352 --> 00:20:31.272
Is that. like. damage to the screen?

485
00:20:31.439 --> 00:20:32.815
Yeah. Something's fried it.

486
00:20:32.982 --> 00:20:35.443
What the crap?

487
00:20:35.609 --> 00:20:37.403
We always carry gamma ray detectors

488
00:20:37.570 --> 00:20:39.697
to look out for radiation
spikes on the ranch.

489
00:20:39.864 --> 00:20:43.033
because they occasionally
appear out of nowhere.

490
00:20:43.200 --> 00:20:46.996
Well. right after that
1.2-gigahertz signal showed up.

491
00:20:47.163 --> 00:20:48.873
I suddenly noticed that the screen

492
00:20:49.039 --> 00:20:51.000
on my gamma ray detector was busted

493
00:20:51.125 --> 00:20:53.377
and the device was fried.

494
00:20:53.586 --> 00:20:56.505
Was this caused
by whatever sent that signal?

495
00:20:56.672 --> 00:20:58.424
That made me want to see if Erik and I

496
00:20:58.591 --> 00:21:00.092
could get something else to happen

497
00:21:00.259 --> 00:21:02.803
by broadcasting his 1.2-gigahertz signal

498
00:21:02.928 --> 00:21:04.555
from over at Homestead Three.

499
00:21:04.722 --> 00:21:07.641
Hey. Erik. It's Travis. You copy?

500
00:21:07.767 --> 00:21:08.976
Yeah. Travis.

501
00:21:09.143 --> 00:21:10.811
Go ahead.

502
00:21:10.978 --> 00:21:13.522
If you want to do a test on
that 1.2-gigahertz transmitter

503
00:21:13.689 --> 00:21:15.816
from the table. that would be good.

504
00:21:15.983 --> 00:21:17.276
Yeah. Travis.

505
00:21:17.443 --> 00:21:19.403
Let me turn that on. Stand by.

506
00:21:26.076 --> 00:21:28.370
All right. You should
be seeing it. We've got it

507
00:21:28.537 --> 00:21:30.956
on the spectrum analyzers here.

508
00:21:31.123 --> 00:21:34.084
Well...

509
00:21:34.251 --> 00:21:37.046
- No.
- Not seeing it.

510
00:21:37.213 --> 00:21:38.798
Nope. nothing.

511
00:21:38.964 --> 00:21:43.260
I'm tuned up to 1.2.
but I'm not seeing any spikes.

512
00:21:43.469 --> 00:21:45.304
Are you seeing it down there?

513
00:21:45.471 --> 00:21:47.097
Negative.

514
00:21:47.306 --> 00:21:49.626
I... As close as that is. we
shouldn't have any difficulty.

515
00:21:49.725 --> 00:21:51.285
I mean. look. I've picked that thing up

